<br>
Destruction: never beaten it. Got to 19 mobs a couple of times. The first time with two minutes remaining there were no mobs. We didn't know how it worked or how many we had to kill and we thought we had won. Then just after the final minute mark, two mobs spawned catching us off guard. Didn't get them dead and we lost. Since then it worked normally until last night. We started, one mob. Killed it, no mobs. One minute timer goes off, then a second mob came. Killed it, no mobs. After the second minute timer a few came and it was more normal with continuous mobs. Since we were in AE mode, one mob wasn't very efficient and the dead time cost us. Have you all had this kind of irregularity?<br>
<br>
As for difficulty, any elemental melee can off tank with Bard AE slow as the only slow. Yeah, even bards. Shaman epic and group heal HoT are a big help to the cleric. It's just getting enough DPS for us. Keeping the mobs in AE range and casters controlling aggro.<br>
<br>
Ingenuity: for elemental groups, get two pet classes. Beast and mage work well. Farm the bane weapons before engaging the boss because it reduces the amount of time you have to keep your tank standing. You can avoid instant aggro by saying begin out of direct los (ie. don't stand on the ramp, stand completely off the platform and keep hailing till you find a spot where he responds). Boss aggro range is huge, so keep your group tight to the wall while you farm. Position the group between two mini-platforms and one will always have a mob waiting for you.  Arm the pets first. Tank can loot his right before pulling. Alternating cleric chain casting CH and shaman or druid splash healing in between will keep a 12k tank up. IMO, the easiest trial. <br>
<br>
Fear: Lots of fun, and yes you can lose without wiping. Just don't kill enough and they go poof. I've been the dedicated fearer several times and this has never been a problem. Just make sure you are using screech and not song of midnight. And keep in mind the small range. Get in their face. I think we make better fearers then chanters because we can take a few hits while trying to get it to stick.<br>
<br>
This requires a group that can pay attention and can react quickly. Sometimes feared mobs get stuck in the corners. Make sure your casters know not to stand next to them. Or fear breaks and they get whacked. These guys hit harder than the unfearables (they have a proc of some kind). <br>
<br>
Comment on the original post, bard fear does not overwrite others. When back when, I used to fear kite with my brother's ranger. He used panic animal, I used screech. They stack, in the sense that when one of us got the worn off message the animal was still feared by the other. This worked great because as we refreshed our respective fears it was still fleeing. I think it works like our slows plus caster slow. The mob has both slows on him, but only one is active. One wears off the other is still there.<br>
<br>
Efficiency: Mezzing is a waste of time, even more so for elemental groups who don't have the DPS to spare. As long as you have a tank on the commander and off tank on the elite, any melee can take hits from the soldiers. I just play AE slow and AE MR debuff. The main difficulties we've had is casters avoiding aggro.  I've never been able to time the subsequent AEs, but I'm going to try out the mp3 timer. Thanks for posting it. For the most part though, casters seem able to manage the mana drain. Except for wizards. They just hurt. Even a 6.5k mana cleric can cope, so don't let it psych you out. An epic'd shaman with the group HoT AA can take a lot of pressure off.<br>
<br>
